9. The full architecture

The mature version looks like this:

STATE
  what currently exists
DELTA
  what is changing
TRANSITION
  what produces the change
CONSTRAINT
  what changes are permitted
INVARIANT
  what must survive the change
HISTORY
  what changes have already occurred
PREDICTION
  what change is expected next
ERROR
  difference between expected and actual delta
ADAPTATION
  change to the model or rule
INTENT
  desired future state
CONTROL
  selected delta intended to move toward it
CREATION
  composition of rules, constraints, and deltas
  to produce a previously unrealized trajectory

In compact code:

while system.is_active():
    observation = system.observe()
    predicted_delta = system.predict_delta(observation)
    desired_delta = system.choose_delta(
        observation=observation,
        prediction=predicted_delta,
        goal=system.goal,
    )
    permitted_delta = system.constraints.project(
        desired_delta
    )
    previous_state = system.state
    system.state = apply_delta(
        system.state,
        permitted_delta,
    )
    actual_delta = system.measure_delta(
        previous_state,
        system.state,
    )
    prediction_error = actual_delta - predicted_delta
    system.learn(prediction_error)
    system.record(actual_delta)

That is the moving manuscript turned into runtime.

The code is not merely describing the system.

It becomes the mechanism through which:

* state becomes motion,
* motion becomes history,
* history becomes learning,
* learning changes future motion,
* and discovered invariants become materials for deliberate creation.

The final transition is:

\text{Mathematics}
\rightarrow
\text{Dynamics}
\rightarrow
\text{Deltas}
\rightarrow
\text{Algorithms}
\rightarrow
\text{Programs}
\rightarrow
\text{Adaptive systems}
\rightarrow
\text{Designed possibility}

Or in one line:

future = compose(
    present,
    change,
    memory,
    constraint,
    intention,
)

The creator does not command every future frame.

The creator designs the rules by which frames may become one another.